### Rendering Elements

Elements are the smallest building blocks of React apps. An element describes what you want to see on the screen.

---

### Rendering to the DOM

```jsx
import { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client';

const root = createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
const element = <h1>Hello, world</h1>;
root.render(element);
```

### Updating the Rendered Element

React elements are immutable. To update the UI, create a new element and pass it to `root.render()`:

```jsx
function tick() {
  const element = (
    <div>
      <h1>Current Time</h1>
      <h2>{new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}</h2>
    </div>
  );
  root.render(element);
}

setInterval(tick, 1000);
```

### React Only Updates What's Necessary

React DOM compares the element and its children to the previous version and applies only the necessary DOM updates.

| Method | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `createRoot(container)` | Creates a React root |
| `root.render(element)` | Renders the element into the root |
| `root.unmount()` | Destroys the rendered tree |

> **Key Point:** In practice, you call `root.render()` once in your app. State updates within components trigger re-renders automatically.

